of Wisdom examines six central philosophies of living--Socratic, Aristotelian, Stoic, Epicurean, Skeptic, and the Platonist life of late antiquity. The book describes the shared assumptions that allowed these thinkers to conceive of their philosophies as ways of life, as well as the distinctive ideas that led them to widely different conclusions about the best human life. Clearing up many common misperceptions and simplifications, Cooper explains in detail the Socratic devotion to philosophical discussion about human nature, human life, and human good; the Aristotelian focus on the true place of humans within the total system of the natural world; the Stoic commitment to dutifully accepting Zeus's plans; the Epicurean pursuit of pleasure through tranquil activities that exercise perception, thought, and feeling; the Skeptical eschewal of all critical reasoning in forming their beliefs; and, finally, the late Platonist emphasis on spiritual concerns and the eternal realm of Being. Pursuits of Wisdom is essential reading for anyone interested in understanding what the great philosophers of antiquity thought was the true purpose of philosophy--and of life.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aConduct of life. 0aPhilosophy, Ancient. 0aWisdom. 7aPHILOSOPHY / History & Surveys / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh  aAristotelian life.  aAristotle.  aEpicurean life.  aEpicurus.  aHadot.  aPlato.  aPlatonism.  aPlatonist life.  aPlotinus.  aPyrrhonian skepticism.  aSextus Empiricus.  aSkeptic life.  aSocrates.  aSocratic knowledge.  aSocratic life.  aStoic life.  aStoicism.  aStoics.  aancient philosophy.  abiology.  acontemplative life.  adialectic.  aethics.  ahappiness.  ahuman life.  alogic knowledge.  alogic.  ametaphysics.  amoral philosophy.  aphysical theory.  ask